    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>knowledge panel</strong> is the structured information box Google displays on the right side of desktop search results — or at the top on mobile — when it confidently identifies the entity behind a query. It shows key facts about a business, person, or brand: description, logo, hours, social links, and more — pulled from Google's Knowledge Graph.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Desktop position</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Right sidebar</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Mobile position</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Top of results</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~+30% branded CTR</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A knowledge panel is one of the strongest brand signals you can earn in Google Search. It doesn't just display information — it tells every searcher that Google has verified your entity exists and knows what it is. That trust signal converts.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a knowledge panel?</h2>
        <p>Google generates knowledge panels when it has sufficient, consistent entity data from trusted sources to confidently describe what an entity is. The data comes from Google's Knowledge Graph — a structured database of over 500 billion facts about 5 billion entities.</p>
        <p>For businesses, a typical knowledge panel shows:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Business name, logo, and header image</li>
          <li>Category or entity type (e.g., "Software company")</li>
          <li>Description (typically pulled from Wikipedia or Google's own synthesis)</li>
          <li>Website link</li>
          <li>Phone number and address (for local businesses)</li>
          <li>Operating hours</li>
          <li>Aggregate ratings from Google reviews</li>
          <li>Social profile links (LinkedIn, Twitter/X, Facebook)</li>
          <li>"People also search for" related entities</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For people (founders, authors, public figures), panels show name, occupation, birthdate, employer, notable works, and associated entities.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">CTR data from Kalicube</div>
          <p>Kalicube's research across thousands of branded search queries found that businesses with verified, claimed knowledge panels see <strong>approximately 30% higher branded click-through rates</strong> compared to those without. The panel's visual dominance on the SERP drives attention before users even read organic results.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why knowledge panels matter for your brand</h2>
        <p>The knowledge panel is not just an information display — it's a SERP real estate advantage and a trust mechanism.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>SERP dominance on branded searches.</strong> For any search of your brand name, the knowledge panel occupies the entire right column on desktop and the top of the mobile SERP. Competitors' ads or organic results are pushed visually below it.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand credibility at zero cost.</strong> Google only generates panels for entities it has enough confidence to describe. The existence of a panel signals to searchers that your brand is real, established, and verified.</li>
          <li><strong>Information control.</strong> Once claimed, you can suggest edits to description, images, and social links. This gives you partial editorial control over what Google says about your brand on the most visible search real estate you own.</li>
          <li><strong>Zero-click brand exposure.</strong> Searchers who don't click still see your logo, description, and key facts. This is free brand impressions for every branded search — even non-converting ones.</li>
          <li><strong>AI Overview source signal.</strong> Brands with strong Knowledge Graph records (of which a knowledge panel is a visible indicator) are cited more frequently in Google's AI Overview answers for category queries.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google generates a knowledge panel</h2>
        <p>Google creates panels automatically — you cannot request one directly. The trigger is sufficient entity confidence from multiple trusted sources:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Knowledge panel generation logic (simplified)</span><br>
          Search query: <span class="uf-new">"Acme Corporation"</span><br>
          Google matches to KG entity: <span class="uf-new">Q12345678 (Acme Corp)</span><br>
          Confidence check: <span class="uf-comment">Wikipedia + GBP + schema + 40+ citations agree</span><br>
          Threshold met → <span class="uf-status">panel generated</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Panel content sources</span><br>
          Description: <span class="uf-new">Wikipedia intro paragraph (most common) or Google synthesis</span><br>
          Logo: <span class="uf-new">Organization schema logo property or GBP photo</span><br>
          Social links: <span class="uf-new">sameAs in Organization schema</span><br>
          Hours/address: <span class="uf-new">Google Business Profile data</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Claiming vs. earning a knowledge panel</h3>
        <p>Earning a panel requires building sufficient entity signals (see best practices below). Claiming it is a separate step: once a panel exists for your entity, you can verify ownership through Google Search Console, which gives you the ability to suggest edits to the panel's content.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of knowledge panels</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Panel type</th><th>Who gets it</th><th>Key data shown</th><th>How to earn</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Business panel</strong></td>
                <td>Organizations + local businesses</td>
                <td>Logo, hours, address, reviews, social links</td>
                <td>GBP + schema + citations</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Person panel</strong></td>
                <td>Public figures, authors, founders</td>
                <td>Photo, occupation, employer, notable works</td>
                <td>Wikipedia + Person schema + press</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Brand / Product panel</strong></td>
                <td>Consumer brands, apps, software</td>
                <td>Description, category, related products</td>
                <td>Wikipedia + Product schema + reviews</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Place panel</strong></td>
                <td>Landmarks, cities, venues</td>
                <td>Location, photos, hours, ratings</td>
                <td>GBP + structured citations</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real knowledge panel examples</h2>
        <p>Two cases show how different entity types earn and use panels.</p>

        <h3>Example 1: B2B law firm</h3>
        <p>A 12-attorney firm claims their GBP, adds Organization schema with the founding year, practice areas, and sameAs links to LinkedIn and Avvo. A local business editor writes a profile in a regional newspaper. Within 3 months, a knowledge panel appears showing the firm's logo, founding year, description, and partner names. The firm's branded search CTR increases from 41% to 58%.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: SaaS founder building a personal panel</h3>
        <p>A founder publishes 24 articles in industry publications over 6 months (each carrying a byline with Person schema), creates a Wikipedia page citing 3 verifiable achievements, and links their Twitter/X and LinkedIn from Person schema on the company blog author page. A personal knowledge panel appears showing their name, title, company affiliation, and notable work.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Knowledge panel vs. local business panel — what's different?</h2>
        <p>The terms describe overlapping but distinct SERP features.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Knowledge panel (entity panel)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Driven by the Knowledge Graph</li>
              <li>For brands, people, and non-local entities</li>
              <li>Triggered by branded search</li>
              <li>Content sourced from Wikipedia, schema, sameAs</li>
              <li>Claimed via Google Search Console</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Local business panel (GBP panel)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Driven by Google Business Profile</li>
              <li>For businesses with a physical address or service area</li>
              <li>Triggered by local search + branded search</li>
              <li>Content managed directly in GBP dashboard</li>
              <li>Claimed via GBP verification</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 steps to earn a knowledge panel</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Verify your Google Business Profile.</strong> For local businesses, GBP verification is the fastest path. Google's own product feeds directly into the Knowledge Graph and almost always triggers a local business panel.</li>
          <li><strong>Add Organization schema to your homepage.</strong> Include <code>@type</code>, <code>name</code>, <code>url</code>, <code>logo</code>, <code>foundingDate</code>, <code>description</code>, and a <code>sameAs</code> array pointing to Wikipedia, Wikidata, LinkedIn, and other authoritative profiles.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a Wikidata entry.</strong> Wikidata is directly consumed by the Knowledge Graph. Add your entity type (P31), official website (P856), founding date (P571), CEO (P169), and industry (P452). Include a sameAs link to your website.</li>
          <li><strong>Build or improve a Wikipedia article.</strong> Wikipedia is Google's most trusted single source for panel descriptions. If your organization meets Wikipedia's notability criteria, a well-sourced article accelerates panel creation significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Build 50+ consistent citations.</strong> Every major directory — Yelp, Bing Places, Apple Maps, Foursquare, Crunchbase — should show the same name, address, phone, and website URL. Citation consistency tells Google your entity data is reliable.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn authoritative press mentions.</strong> News coverage in publications Google trusts (regional newspapers, industry outlets, Bloomberg, TechCrunch) carries entity signal weight that directory citations cannot replicate.</li>
          <li><strong>Claim the panel once it appears.</strong> Search your brand name, scroll to the panel, click "Claim this knowledge panel," and verify via your Search Console property. This lets you suggest edits to description, logo, and social links.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — not monitoring panel content</div>
          <p>Knowledge panels are edited by Wikipedia volunteers, corrected by Google's algorithms, and can pull outdated data from old citations. Without monthly monitoring, your panel may show an old logo, wrong phone number, or an outdated description without you noticing. Set a monthly calendar reminder to search your brand name and audit the panel.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common knowledge panel mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Waiting for the panel to appear before optimizing.</strong> Entity signals need to be in place for months before a panel triggers. Start the optimization work now, not after you notice the panel is missing.</li>
          <li><strong>Not claiming the panel after it appears.</strong> Unclaimed panels can show wrong images, outdated descriptions, or competitor-associated data. Claiming takes 10 minutes and protects your branded SERP.</li>
          <li><strong>Relying only on GBP for the panel.</strong> GBP alone creates a local business panel but not a full entity knowledge panel. You also need schema markup and off-site authority signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Outdated sameAs links.</strong> If your Twitter handle changed or your Wikipedia URL was updated, old sameAs links break the entity connection. Audit all sameAs targets quarterly.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring why a panel disappeared.</strong> If your panel vanishes, Google lost confidence. The most common causes: Wikipedia article deleted, schema markup removed after a site rebuild, or conflicting NAP data. Audit the full entity signal stack before concluding the panel is gone permanently.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
